A thin body does not equal a healthy body. It doesn’t mean you feel good physically and I am proof. Crazy that society still places such an emphasis on this. I wish I could say working out and getting movement often was a choice I made with out a nudge but that’s not the case. In the last 2 years since giving birth I’ve been in the most discomfort and pain ever in my life. The nudge was the pseudo sciatic pain (too much sitting while working), lower back aches caused by my anterior pelvic tilt (recent pregnancy), neck & upper trap pain (bad posture while breast feeding & computer work). None of those things are visible but I sure do feel them. They affect my quality of life so I’m doing something about it. Strategic strength training will help a lot. Walking has already helped so much and I’m glad because I definitely don’t want pain medication to be my only go to. Come along for the ride as I share a bit more on how I’m addressing these pains. 
Each movement after the two warm up movement was done 2 times with 10-15 reps. 
#pseudosciatica #sciatica #sciaticarelief #sciaticapain #anteriorpelvictilt #techneck

It all started with taking a daily walk in December of 2022 and I’ve been going strong ever since. My best friend at the moment is #movement 🙌🏿 😂 In the past year I’ve experienced some intense pain and discomfort that started in 2020! It’s taken me lots of doctors visits and time to figure it out but long story short, I needed to strengthen and wake up muscles that were not firing, sit less, reduce stress and improve my posture. Sounds simple but whew! Crazy that simple movement made the pain so much better but it’s been a journey getting here and building up to it. My goals have been to strengthen my lower back (back aches), core, glutes and to improve my ability to do basic strength movements like push ups, squats, etc. Basically functional strength for my everyday life. As promised a Full 25 minute workout is available with no sound on YouTube. Put on your own music and follow along 😊 Where are you in your movement journey? #improveposture #functionaltraining #functionalfitness #lowerbackpain

This 90s mushroom bowl haircut is giving me options 🙌🏿
1. Why is the first braid always so ugly? Or is just me? 😅 
2. Having a cut that is primarily on your face makes your forehead want a break sometimes. 
3. Braids are always the answer to needing a hair break. 
4. I feel so powerful and strong with my hair like this. 
5. Yes I put water on my dry hair. I feel like it helps my very blunt hair cut stay tucked. @patternbeauty pomade on my ends also help a lot!
